,"Taunton, , Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Combe Manor, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","West Buckland, Somerset, England":"West Buckland, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1405–1460":"1405–1460","1399–1460":"1399–1460","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1443–1476":"1443–1476","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1443":"1443","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Taunton, , Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Combe Manor, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","West Buckland, Somerset, England":"West Buckland, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1405–1460":"1405–1460","1399–1460":"1399–1460","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1443–1476":"1443–1476","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1443":"1443","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Taunton, , Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Combe Manor, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","West Buckland, Somerset, England":"West Buckland, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Middleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Midthun","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of about ten farmsteads in western Norway named Midtun, from Old Norse <i>mith</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tún</i> ‘enclosure, farmstead’. Compare   Middleton  ."]},{"name":"Melton","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."]},{"name":"Middlebrook","meanings":["English: habitational name from a lost <i>Micklebrook</i> in Blackburn (Lancashire), recorded as <i>Mikelbroc</i> in the 13th century. The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>micel</i> ‘big’ + <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’. The surname has undergone a dissimilatory or folk-etymological change from <i>Mickle-</i> to <i>Middle-</i>."]},{"name":"Milton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the many places called Milton, or sometimes Middleton (see   Middleton  ) and occasionally Melton (see   Melton  ), most of which derive from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ or <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Joan Middleton was born in 1405, in Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. She married Willielmus De Combes in 1425, in Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1460, in her hometown, at the age of 55, and was buried in Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1405–1460":"1405–1460","1399–1460":"1399–1460","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1443–1476":"1443–1476","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1443":"1443","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Taunton, , Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Combe Manor, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Buckland, Somerset, England":"West Buckland, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1405–1460":"1405–1460","1399–1460":"1399–1460","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1443–1476":"1443–1476","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1443":"1443","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Taunton, , Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Combe Manor, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","West Buckland, Somerset, England":"West Buckland, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1405–1460":"1405–1460","1399–1460":"1399–1460","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1443–1476":"1443–1476","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1443":"1443","1476":"1476","1399":"1399","1460":"1460","1405":"1405","Taunton, , Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Combe Manor, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","West Buckland, Somerset, England":"West Buckland, Somerset, Angleterre","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lady Joan Middleton est née en 1405, à Taunton, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Willielmus De Combes en 1425, à Taunton, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Elle est décédée en 1460, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 55 ans, et a été enterrée à Taunton, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1405–1460":"1405–1460","1399–1460":"1399–1460","1426–1502":"1426–1502","1443–1476":"1443–1476","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1443":"1443","1476":"1476","13